FizzBuzz Functions

The FizzBuzz Test is a famous programming interview question. > Write a program that prints the numbers from 1 to 30. But for multiples of three print Fizz instead of the number and for the multiples of five print Buzz. For numbers which are multiples of both three and five print FizzBuzz

In the R chunk below, write a function which will solve this problem. Do not change the function name or parameter name.

Show the results from running your function on the integers 1-20, as well as a sequence of 10 random integers between 0 and 100. (This code is already written for you).

fizzbuzz <- function(x) {
  # FizzBuzz code goes here
  # This is a crude way to solve this problem, and not the most efficient, 
  # but it's only using things you know at the moment...
  # If you're still writing code like this at the end of class, I've failed :)
  for (i in x) {
    if (i %% 15 == 0) {        # Handle multiples of 3 and 5 (so 15) first
      str <- "FizzBuzz"
    } else if (i %% 5 == 0) { # Then, you know anything that isn't a multiple of
      str <- "Buzz"           # 15 and is a multiple of 5 isn't divisible by 3
    } else if (i %% 3 == 0) { # And so if something isn't divisible by 5, you 
      str <- "Fizz"           # also need to check divisibility by 3
    } else {
      str <- as.character(i)  # Then, if none of those conditions hold, print the 
    }                         # number
    print(str)
  }
}

In the sas chunk, write similar code which will solve this problem.

proc printto log="saslog.log" new;
proc iml;

start fizzbuzz(x);
/* FizzBuzz code goes here */
  a = '';
  IF MOD(x, 5)=0 THEN DO;
      a = cats(a,"Fizz");
  END;
  if MOD(x,3)=0 THEN DO;
      a = cats(a,"Buzz");
  END;
  IF a = '' THEN DO;
      a = cats(a, x);
  END;
  RETURN a;
finish;

x1 = repeat(0, 20); /* initialize x1 */
fb1 = repeat("        ", 20);
do i = 1 to 20;
  x1[i] = i;
  fb1[i] = fizzbuzz(x1[i]);
end;

x2 = repeat(0, 10); /* initialize x2 */
fb2 = repeat("xxxxxxxx", 10); /* initialize fb2 */
do i = 1 to 10;
  x2[i] = rand("Integer", 1, 100);
  fb2[i] = fizzbuzz(x2[i]);
end;

print x1 fb1, x2 fb2;

quit;

Exploring Packages and Modules

R Package: ishihara

Find an R package which is interesting to you. Fill in the package name above, and describe or demonstrate some feature of the package here.

I found a tweet announcing the ishihara R package for R. Ishihara plates are plates used to test for colorblindness, and this package claims to be able to generate them. A couple of caveats this is a very beta package, so most things dont work as well as they should. Case in point, the package only seems to work with letters that dont have multiple pieces (i, j) or holes (a, b, d).

# devtools::install_github("njtierney/ishihara")
library(ishihara)
library(ggplot2)

set.seed(2020-05-10)
word <- strsplit("Luck", "")[[1]] # Split a word into letters
plots <- as.list(word) # Make lists to store the data/plots in
data <- as.list(word)
# Make a list of 4 different color scales
scales <- list(scale_fill_discrete(), 
               scale_fill_brewer(palette = 3), 
               scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", "green")), 
               scale_fill_manual(values = c("purple", "yellow")))

# Compute the data
for(i in 1:length(word)) {
  data[[i]] <- ishihara_data(word[i])
} 

# Make the plots
for(i in 1:length(word)) {
  plots[[i]] <- gg_ishihara(data[[i]]) + scales[[i]]
}

library(gridExtra) # Combine plots
grid.arrange(grobs = plots, ncol = 4)
